entries.meaning: Excess of weight or value; something more than an equivalent.

verbs.description: overbalance (third-person singular simple present overbalances, present participle overbalancing, simple past and past participle overbalanced)

entries.meaning: To be more important than; to outweigh. [from 16th c.]
examples: I thought of giving up this club, which was expensive and of no service to me, and the amusement overbalanced by the late hours.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause an imbalance in (something) by means of excess weight or numbers. [from 17th c.]
(transitive) To throw (someone or something) off balance; to cause to capsize. [from 19th c.]
(intransitive) To lose one's balance; to fall over. [from 19th c.]
